## Installation

### Clone Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/Q-GAP.git

cd Q-GAP
```

---

### Create Environment

Using Conda:

```bash
conda create -n qgap python=3.10

conda activate qgap
```

---

### Install Dependencies

```bash
pip install torch

pip install torch-geometric

pip install networkx

pip install matplotlib

pip install pandas

pip install numpy

pip install pennylane
```

---

## Requirements

### Software

* Python 3.10+
* PyTorch
* PyTorch Geometric
* PennyLane
* NetworkX
* NumPy
* Pandas
* Matplotlib

### Hardware

Recommended:

* Intel Core i7 or higher
* 16 GB RAM
* NVIDIA GPU with CUDA support

Experiments reported in the paper were executed using CUDA-enabled GPU acceleration.

---

## Configuration

All experiment parameters can be modified in:

```text
config.py
```

Example:

```python
SUBSTRATE_NODES = 80

VNR_MIN_NODES = 2

VNR_MAX_NODES = 6

EPISODES = 5000

LEARNING_RATE = 0.0003

BASELINE = "Q-GAP"
```

Supported baselines:

```python
BASELINE = "PPO"

BASELINE = "PPO+GAT"

BASELINE = "Quantum-PPO"

BASELINE = "DL-ViNE"

BASELINE = "Q-GAP"
```

---

## Running Experiments

Run training:

```bash
python main.py
```

---

## Evaluation Metrics

The framework evaluates:

### Request Acceptance Ratio (RAC)

Percentage of Virtual Network Requests successfully embedded.

### Revenue-to-Cost Ratio (R2C)

Measures embedding efficiency.

### Long-Term Average Revenue (LAR)

Evaluates long-term profitability.

### CPU Utilization

Percentage of substrate CPU resources utilized.

### Bandwidth Utilization

Percentage of substrate bandwidth resources utilized.

### Training Loss

Actor and Critic optimization performance.

### Policy Entropy

Exploration behavior during learning.

---

## Experimental Results

### Baseline Comparison

| Method      | RAC (%) |
| ----------- | ------- |
| PPO         | 55.53   |
| PPO+GAT     | 75.14   |
| Quantum-PPO | 80.02   |
| DL-ViNE     | 82.15   |
| Q-GAP       | 87.31   |

The proposed Q-GAP framework achieves the highest acceptance ratio among all evaluated methods.

